# Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the Kent 11+ Schools Hub project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` package (version 2.0.1) using npm
- Updated `package.json` to include the new dependency
- Generated `package-lock.json` for consistent dependency resolution

### 2. Code Integration
Modified `src/App.js`:
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/react";`
- Added `<Analytics />` component at the end of the main App component (after `</BrowserRouter>` and before the closing `</div>`)

## Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel documentation (https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart), I implemented the React/Create React App integration pattern:

1. **Framework Detection**: Identified this as a Create React App project based on:
   - `react-scripts` in package.json
   - Project structure with src/App.js as the main component
   - Use of CRACO for custom configuration

2. **Integration Pattern**: Used the recommended pattern for React applications:
   - Imported from `@vercel/analytics/react` (React-specific export)
   - Placed the `<Analytics />` component at the root level of the App component
   - Component placement ensures tracking across all routes (inside BrowserRouter context)

3. **Verification**: 
   - Build completed successfully with no errors
   - No tests were present to run, but build process validated the integration
   - No ESLint configuration found, but build passed without issues

## Next Steps

To activate analytics tracking:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Enable Analytics in the Vercel project dashboard
3. Analytics will automatically start tracking page views and visitor data

## Files Modified

- `frontend/package.json` - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- `frontend/package-lock.json` - New file for dependency lock
- `frontend/src/App.js` - Added Analytics import and component

All changes follow React best practices and maintain the existing code structure without breaking any functionality.
